# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: openshift
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:openshift/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:openshift/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:openshift/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:openshift/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:openshift/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:openshift/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:openshift/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:openshift/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:openshift/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:openshift/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:openshift/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:openshift/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:openshift/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:openshift/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:openshift/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:openshift/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:openshift/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:openshift/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:openshift/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:openshift/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:openshift/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:openshift/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:openshift/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:openshift/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:openshift/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:openshift/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:openshift/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:openshift/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:openshift/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:openshift/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:openshift/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:openshift/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:openshift/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:openshift/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:openshift/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:openshift/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:openshift/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:openshift/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:openshift/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:openshift/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:openshift/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:openshift/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:openshift/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:openshift/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:openshift/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:openshift/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:openshift/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:openshift/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:openshift/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:openshift/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:openshift/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:openshift/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:openshift/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:openshift/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:openshift/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:openshift/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:openshift/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:openshift/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:openshift/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:openshift/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:openshift/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:openshift/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:openshift/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:openshift/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:openshift/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:openshift/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:openshift/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:openshift/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:openshift/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:openshift/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:openshift/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:openshift/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:openshift/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:openshift/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:openshift/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:openshift/openshift] The family's other products provide this platform through different environments.
[src:openshift/openshift] Deployment methods include self-managed; cloud native under **ROSA** (Red Hat OpenShift Service on AWS), **ARO** (Azure Red Hat OpenShift) and **RHOIC** (Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud); OpenShift Online as software as a service; and OpenShift Dedicated as a managed service.
[src:openshift/openshift] The OpenShift Console has developer and administrator oriented views.
[src:openshift/openshift] Administrator views allow one to monitor container resources and health, manage users and work with operators.
[src:openshift/openshift] Developer views are oriented around working with application resources within a namespace.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift also provides a CLI that supports a superset of the actions provided by the Kubernetes CLI.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift originated from Red Hat's acquisition of Makara, a company marketing a platform as a service (PaaS) based on Linux containers, in November 2010.
[src:openshift/openshift] It was announced in May 2011 as proprietary technology and only became open-source in May 2012.
[src:openshift/openshift] Until version 3, released in June 2015, OpenShift used custom developed technologies.
[src:openshift/openshift] Version 3 adopted Docker as the container technology and Kubernetes as the orchestration engine.
[src:openshift/openshift] Version 4 further changed the architecture, notably adopting CRI-O as the container runtime (and Podman for interacting with pods and containers), and Buildah as the container build tool, thus removing the dependency on Docker.
[src:openshift/openshift] Online offered version 2 of the OKD project source code, which is also available under the Apache License Version 2.0.
[src:openshift/openshift] This version supported a variety of languages, frameworks, and databases via pre-built "cartridges" running under resource-quota "gears".
[src:openshift/openshift] Developers could add other languages, databases, or components via the OpenShift Cartridge application programming interface.
[src:openshift/openshift] This was deprecated in favour of OpenShift 3, and was withdrawn on 30 September 2017 for non-paying customers and 31 December 2017 for paying customers.
[src:openshift/openshift] The main difference between OpenShift and vanilla Kubernetes is its extension of the platform with build-related artifacts as first-class Kubernetes resources upon which standard Kubernetes operations can apply.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift's *oc* client offers a superset of the standard *kubectl* (Kubernetes standard client) capabilities., including direct interaction with build resources via sub-commands like *new-build* or *start-build*.
[src:openshift/openshift] It also provided out of the box an OpenShift-native pod builds technology called Source-to-Image (S2I), though this is slowly being phased out in favor of Tekton, a cloud-native CI/CD framework for Kubernetes.
[src:openshift/openshift] Unique resources like ImageStreams (a sequence of pointers to images which can be associated with deployments) and Templates (a packaging mechanism for application components).
[src:openshift/openshift] The *new-app* command, which initiates an application deployment, automatically applies the *app* label (with the value of the label taken from the *--name* argument) to all created resources, simplifying management.
[src:openshift/openshift] Support for multiple infrastructure platforms, including AWS, Azure, IBM Cloud, vSphere, and bare metal.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift’s implementation of Deployment, called DeploymentConfig is logic-based in comparison to Kubernetes' controller-based Deployment objects.
[src:openshift/openshift] As of v4.5, OpenShift is steering more towards Deployments by changing the default behavior of its CLI.
[src:openshift/openshift] An embedded OperatorHub, a web GUI for browsing and installing a library of Kubernetes Operators packaged for easy life cycle management, including Red Hat authored Operators, Red Hat Certified Operators and Community Operators.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift v4 tightly controls the operating systems for "control plane" components.
[src:openshift/openshift] They must run on Red Hat CoreOS, enabling automated, reliable upgrades and patches.
[src:openshift/openshift] The compute (worker) nodes can run any Linux OS or even Windows.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift introduced the concept of *routes* -- points of traffic ingress into the cluster.
[src:openshift/openshift] This later influenced the Kubernetes ingress concept.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift also bundles various software components from the Kubernetes ecosystem for enhanced functionality.
[src:openshift/openshift] For observability, it includes Prometheus, Fluentd, Vector, Loki, and Istio (branded as Red Hat Service Mesh, based on the Maistra open source project).
[src:openshift/openshift] OKD, known until August 2018 as OpenShift Origin (Origin Community Distribution) is the upstream community project for OpenShift.
[src:openshift/openshift] Built around a core of CRI-O container runtime and Kubernetes cluster management, OKD is augmented by application life cycle management functionality and DevOps tooling.
[src:openshift/openshift] All source code for the OKD project is available under the Apache License (Version 2.0) on GitHub.
[src:openshift/openshift] Red Hat OpenShift Online (RHOO) is a public cloud application development and hosting software as a service (SaaS) that runs on AWS and IBM Cloud.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift Online is limited to running containers that do not require root.
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift Dedicated (OSD) is Red Hat's managed private cluster offering on the marketplaces of Amazon Web Services (AWS), IBM Cloud, Google Cloud Platform (GCP) since December 2016.
[src:openshift/openshift] A similar managed service is offered on Microsoft Azure under the name Azure Red Hat OpenShift (ARO).
[src:openshift/openshift] OpenShift Data Foundation (ODF) provides cloud-native storage, data management and data protection for applications running on the OpenShift platform in cloud, on-premises, and hybrid/multi-cloud environments.
[src:openshift/openshift] Red Hat OpenShift Database Access (RHODA) is a capability for managed OpenShift environments (OSD and ROSA) that enables administrators to set up connections to database-as-a-service offerings from different providers.
[src:openshift/openshift] Its initial alpha release included support for MongoDB Atlas for MongoDB and Crunchy Bridge for PostgreSQL.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:openshift/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat has become associated to a large extent with its enterprise operating system Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:openshift/red-hat] Having grown significantly beyond just Linux, it also includes the OpenShift Container Platform, Ansible Automation Platform, and Red Hat AI.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat had acquired the open-source enterprise middleware vendor JBoss.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat now offers OpenShift Virtualization, which replaces the long retired product Red Hat Virtualization (RHV), an enterprise virtualization product.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat provides operating system platforms, middleware, applications, management products, support, training, and consulting services.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat creates, maintains, and contributes to many free software projects.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It has acquired the codebases of several proprietary software products through corporate mergers and acquisitions, and has released such software under open source licenses.
[src:openshift/red-hat] As of June 2026, Red Hat is the fourth largest corporate contributor to the Linux kernel after Intel, Meta, and Google.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It now operates as an independent subsidiary.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Effective January 12, 2026 Red Hat converted (legal process known as "conversion") from a corporation and as Red Hat, Inc. to then be a limited liability company with new formal name Red Hat, LLC.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 1993, Bob Young incorporated the ACC Corporation, a catalog business that sold Linux and Unix software accessories.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 1994, Marc Ewing created his own Linux distribution, which he named Red Hat Linux (associated with the time Ewing wore a red Cornell University lacrosse hat, given to him by his grandfather, while attending Carnegie Mellon University).
[src:openshift/red-hat] Ewing released the software in October, and it became known as the Halloween release.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Young bought Ewing's business in 1995, and the two merged to become Red Hat Software, with Young serving as chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat went public on August 11, 1999, achieving—at the time—the eighth-biggest first-day gain in the history of Wall Street.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Matthew Szulik succeeded Bob Young as CEO in December of that year.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Bob Young went on to found the online print on demand and self-publishing company, Lulu in 2002.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On November 15, 1999, Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Cygnus provided commercial support for free software and housed maintainers of GNU software products such as the GNU Debugger and GNU Binutils.
[src:openshift/red-hat] One of the founders of Cygnus, Michael Tiemann, became the chief technical officer of Red Hat and by 2008 the vice president of open-source affairs.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Later Red Hat acquired WireSpeed, C2Net, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and Akopia.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In February 2000, *InfoWorld* awarded Red Hat its fourth consecutive "Operating System Product of the Year" award for Red Hat Linux 6.1.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Planning Technologies, Inc. in 2001 and AOL's iPlanet directory and certificate-server software in 2004.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat moved its headquarters from Durham to North Carolina State University's Centennial Campus in Raleigh, North Carolina in February 2002.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In the following month Red Hat introduced Red Hat Linux Advanced Server, later renamed Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL).
[src:openshift/red-hat] Dell, IBM, HP and Oracle Corporation announced their support of the platform.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In December 2005, *CIO Insight* magazine conducted its annual "Vendor Value Survey", in which Red Hat ranked #1 in value for the second year in a row.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat stock became part of the NASDAQ-100 on December 19, 2005.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss on June 5, 2006, and JBoss became a division of Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On September 18, 2006, Red Hat released the Red Hat Application Stack, which integrated the JBoss technology and which was certified by other well-known software vendors.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On December 12, 2006, Red Hat stock moved from trading on NASDAQ (RHAT) to the New York Stock Exchange (RHT).
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2007 Red Hat acquired MetaMatrix and made an agreement with Exadel to distribute its software.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On March 15, 2007, Red Hat released Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5, and in June acquired Mobicents.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On March 13, 2008, Red Hat acquired Amentra, a provider of systems integration services for service-oriented architecture, business process management, systems development, and enterprise data services.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On July 27, 2009, Red Hat replaced CIT Group in Standard and Poor's 500 stock index, a diversified index of 500 leading companies of the U.S. economy.
[src:openshift/red-hat] This was reported as a major milestone for Linux.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On December 15, 2009, it was reported that Red Hat would pay US$8.8 million to settle a class action lawsuit related to the restatement of financial results from July 2004.
[src:openshift/red-hat] District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat reached the proposed settlement agreement and recorded a one-time charge of US$8.8 million for the quarter that ended Nov.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On January 10, 2011, Red Hat announced that it would expand its headquarters in two phases, adding 540 employees to the Raleigh operation, and investing over US$109 million.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The state of North Carolina is offering up to US$15 million in incentives.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The second phase involves "expansion into new technologies such as software virtualization and technology cloud offerings".
[src:openshift/red-hat] On August 25, 2011, Red Hat announced it would move about 600 employees from the N.C.
[src:openshift/red-hat] State Centennial Campus to the Two Progress Plaza building.
[src:openshift/red-hat] A ribbon cutting ceremony was held on June 24, 2013, in the re-branded Red Hat Headquarters.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2012, Red Hat became the first one-billion dollar open-source company, reaching US$1.13 billion in annual revenue during its fiscal year.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat passed the $2 billion benchmark in 2015.
[src:openshift/red-hat] As of February 2018 the company's annual revenue was nearly $3 billion.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On October 16, 2015, Red Hat announced its acquisition of IT automation startup Ansible, rumored for an estimated US$100 million.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In June 2017, Red Hat announced Red Hat Hyperconverged Infrastructure (RHHI) 1.0 software product.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On October 28, 2018, IBM announced its intent to acquire Red Hat for US$34 billion, in one of its largest-ever acquisitions.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The company will operate out of IBM's Hybrid Cloud division.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Microsoft, Amazon, and Google reportedly also considered buying Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Six months later, on May 3, 2019, the US Department of Justice concluded its review of IBM's proposed Red Hat acquisition, and according to Steven J.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Vaughan-Nichols "essentially approved the IBM/Red Hat deal".
[src:openshift/red-hat] The acquisition was closed on July 9, 2019.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat is the primary sponsor of the Fedora Project, a community-supported free software project that aims to promote the rapid progress of free and open-source software and content.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat operates on a business model based on open-source software, development within a community, professional quality assurance, and subscription-based customer support.
[src:openshift/red-hat] They produce open-source code so that more programmers can make adaptations and improvements.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat sells subscriptions for the support, training, and integration services that help customers in using their open-source software products.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Customers pay one set price for unlimited access to services such as Red Hat Network and up to 24/7 support.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In September 2014, however, CEO Jim Whitehurst announced that Red Hat was "in the midst of a major shift from client-server to cloud-mobile".
[src:openshift/red-hat] Rich Bynum, a member of Red Hat's legal team, attributes Linux's success and rapid development partially to open-source business models, including Red Hat's.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat's links to branches of Israel's military and statements of support for Israeli associates has also led to some controversy and calls for boycott during the ongoing conflict in Gaza.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Air Force and US Department of Defense supplier, working closely with Lockheed Martin on warfare-related AI capabilities.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2026, a brochure titled "Compress the kill cycle with Red Hat Device Edge" surfaced, but it was promptly removed from Red Hat websites.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat engineers worked with the One Laptop per Child initiative (a non-profit organization established by members of the MIT Media Lab) to design and produce an inexpensive laptop and try to provide every child in the world with access to open communication, open knowledge, and open learning.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The XO-4 laptop, the last machine the project produced (in 2012), runs a slimmed-down version of Fedora 17 as its operating system.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Avi Kivity began the development of KVM in mid-2006 at Qumranet, a technology startup company that was acquired by Red Hat in 2008.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It has several employees working full-time on Evolution, the official personal information manager for GNOME.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Init system and system/service manager for Linux systems.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Network-capable sound server program distributed via the freedesktop.org project.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Dogtail, an open-source automated graphical user interface (GUI) test framework initially developed by Red Hat, consists of free software released under the GNU General Public License (GPL) and is written in Python.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It allows developers to build and test their applications.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat announced the release of Dogtail at the 2006 Red Hat Summit.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat MRG is a clustering product intended for integrated high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:openshift/red-hat] The acronym MRG stands for "Messaging Realtime Grid".
[src:openshift/red-hat] As of 2011, Red Hat works with the Condor High-Throughput Computing System community and also provides support for the software.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The Tuna performance-monitoring tool runs in the MRG environment.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat produced the online publication Opensource.com since January 20, 2010.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The site highlights ways open-source principles apply in domains other than software development.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The site tracks the application of open-source philosophy to business, education, government, law, health, and life.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The company originally produced a newsletter called Under the Brim.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Wide Open magazine first appeared in March 2004, as a means for Red Hat to share technical content with subscribers regularly.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The Under the Brim newsletter and Wide Open magazine merged in November 2004, to become *Red Hat Magazine*.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In January 2010, *Red Hat Magazine* became Opensource.com.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In April 2023 Red Hat went through company layoffs and laid off the team maintaining Opensource.com.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2007, Red Hat announced that it had reached an agreement with some free software and open-source (FOSS) companies that allowed it to make a distribution portal called Red Hat Exchange, reselling FOSS software with the original branding intact.
[src:openshift/red-hat] However, by 2010, Red Hat had abandoned the Exchange program to focus their efforts more on their Open Source Channel Alliance which began in April 2009.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat build of Keycloak (formerly known as Red Hat Single Sign-On) is a software product to allow single sign-on with Identity Management and Access Management aimed at modern applications and services.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It is based on the open-source project Keycloak, which acts as an upstream project.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat Subscription Management (RHSM) combines content delivery with subscription management.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat is the largest contributor to the Ceph Storage SDS project : Block, File & Object Storage which runs on industry-standard x86 servers and Ethernet IP as well as ARM, InfiniBand, and other technologies.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Ceph aims primarily for completely distributed operation without a single point of failure, scalable to the exabyte level.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Ceph replicates data and makes it fault-tolerant, using commodity hardware and requiring no specific hardware support.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Ceph's system offers disaster recovery and data redundancy through techniques such as replication, erasure coding, snapshots and storage cloning.
[src:openshift/red-hat] As a result of its design, the system is both self-healing and self-managing, aiming to minimize administration time and other costs.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In this way, administrators have a single, consolidated system that avoids silos and collects the storage within a common management framework.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Ceph consolidates several storage use cases and improves resource utilization.
[src:openshift/red-hat] It also lets an organization deploy servers where needed.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat operates OpenShift, a cloud computing platform as a service, supporting applications written in Node.js, PHP, Perl, Python, Ruby, JavaEE and more.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On July 31, 2018, Red Hat announced the release of Istio 1.0, a microservices management program used in tandem with the Kubernetes platform.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The software purports to provide "traffic management, service identity and security, policy enforcement and telemetry" services in order to streamline Kubernetes use under the various Fedora-based operating systems.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat's Brian Redbeard Harring described Istio as "aiming to be a control plane, similar to the Kubernetes control plane, for configuring a series of proxy servers that get injected between application components".
[src:openshift/red-hat] Also Red Hat is the second largest contributor to Kubernetes code itself, after Google.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat markets a version of OpenStack which helps manage a data center in the manner of cloud computing.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat CloudForms provides management of virtual machines, instances and containers based on VMware vSphere, Red Hat Virtualization, Microsoft Hyper-V, OpenStack, Amazon EC2, Google Cloud Platform, Microsoft Azure, and Red Hat OpenShift.
[src:openshift/red-hat] CloudForms is based on the ManageIQ project that Red Hat open sourced.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Code in ManageIQ is from the over US$100 million acquisition of ManageIQ in 2012.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Container Linux (formerly CoreOS Linux) is a discontinued open-source lightweight operating system based on the Linux kernel and designed for providing infrastructure to clustered deployments.
[src:openshift/red-hat] As an operating system, Container Linux provided only the minimal functionality required for deploying applications inside software containers, together with built-in mechanisms for service discovery and configuration sharing.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat contributed, with several software developers, to LibreOffice, a free and open-source office suite.
[src:openshift/red-hat] However, in 2023, Red Hat announced they were not going to include LibreOffice in RHEL 10, citing the ability to download LibreOffice from Flatpak on RHEL desktops.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat also organises "Open Source Day" events where multiple partners show their open-source technologies.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat was one of the largest contributors to the X Window System.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Started in 2008, by Red Hat developer Kristian Høgsberg, with the aim of replacing the X Windows System.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Over and above Red Hat's major products and acquisitions, Red Hat programmers have produced software programming-tools and utilities to supplement standard Unix and Linux software.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Some of these Red Hat "products" have found their way from specifically Red Hat operating environments via open-source channels to a wider community.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The Red Hat website lists the organization's major involvements in free and open-source software projects.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat Czech s.r.o. is a research and development arm of Red Hat, based in Brno, Czech Republic.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The subsidiary was formed in 2006 and has 1,180 employees (2019).
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat chose to enter the Czech Republic in 2006 over other locations due to the country's embrace of open-source.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The subsidiary expanded in 2017 to a second location in the Brno Technology Park to accommodate an additional 350 employees.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2016, Red Hat Czech reported revenue of CZK 1,002 million (FY 2016), and net income of CZK 123 million (FY 2016), with assets of CZK 420 million (FY 2016)|CZK 325 million (FY 2015).
[src:openshift/red-hat] The group was named the "Most progressive employer of the year" in the Czech Republic in 2010, and the "Best Employer in the Czech Republic" for large scale companies in 2011 by Aon.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2000, Red Hat created the subsidiary **Red Hat India** to deliver Red Hat software, support, and services to Indian customers.
[src:openshift/red-hat] As of today (2025 December) 1800 employees work for Red Hat India.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Colin Tenwick, former vice president and general manager of Red Hat EMEA, said Red Hat India was opened "in response to the rapid adoption of Red Hat Linux in the subcontinent.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Demand for open-source solutions from the Indian markets is rising and Red Hat wants to play a major role in this region." Red Hat India has worked with local companies to enable the adoption of open-source technology in both government and education.
[src:openshift/red-hat] In 2006, Red Hat India had a distribution network of more than 70 channel partners spanning 27 cities across India.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat India's channel partners included MarkCraft Solutions, Ashtech Infotech Pvt Ltd., Efensys Technologies, Embee Software, Allied Digital Services, and Softcell Technologies.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Distributors include Integra Micro Systems and Ingram Micro.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat's first major acquisition involved Delix Computer GmbH-Linux Div, the Linux-based operating-system division of Delix Computer, a German computer company, on July 30, 1999.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat acquired Cygnus Solutions, a company that provided commercial support for free software, on January 11, 2000 – it was the company's largest acquisition, for US$674 million.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Michael Tiemann, co-founder of Cygnus, served as the chief technical officer of Red Hat after the acquisition.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Red Hat made the most acquisitions in 2000 with five: Cygnus Solutions, Bluecurve, Wirespeed Communications, Hell's Kitchen Systems, and C2Net.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On June 5, 2006, Red Hat acquired open-source middleware provider JBoss for US$420 million and integrated it as its own division of Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] On December 14, 1998, Red Hat made its first divestment, when Intel and Netscape acquired undisclosed minority stakes in the company.
[src:openshift/red-hat] The next year, on March 9, 1999, Compaq, IBM, Dell and Novell each acquired undisclosed minority stakes in Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Netscape Security-Certain Asts was acquired from Netscape Security Solutions.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Intel Corporation acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] Compaq acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
[src:openshift/red-hat] IBM acquired a minority stake in Red Hat.
